<Base title="Scholar case studies" compactHeader={true}>
  <p class="ar-title" lang="ar" dir="rtl">تراجم العلماء</p>
  <h2>Scholar case studies</h2>
  <p class="summary">Sourced biographical-and-methodological sketches of four scholars whose names are central to the Salafī movement and to its disagreement with the classical Sunnī mainstream — Ibn Taymiyya, Muḥammad Nāṣir al-Dīn al-Albānī, ʿAbd al-ʿAzīz ibn Bāz, and Muḥammad ibn al-ʿUthaymīn. For each: a biographical snapshot, the scholar's methodology, their influence, the documented critiques from named Sunnī scholars, and a closing note on where the position aligns with — and departs from — the classical Sunnī mainstream.</p>

  <p class="standards">The standard followed here is the same as the rest of the site: every claim is sourced; named critics are real scholars with real works; respect for genuine learning is preserved even where disagreement is total. None of these men is dismissed.</p>

  <h3>Ibn Taymiyya (Taqī al-Dīn Aḥmad ibn ʿAbd al-Ḥalīm) — d. 728 AH / 1328 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in Ḥarrān (modern southeastern Turkey, 1263 CE); his family fled the Mongol invasions and settled in Damascus when he was a child. Educated in the Ḥanbalī madhhab and rose to prominence as a polemicist and jurist. Imprisoned multiple times by the Mamlūk authorities in Damascus and Cairo over various rulings (including a controversial fatwa on triple-divorce, his rejection of certain Sufi practices, and his treatment of ziyāra). Died in the Damascus citadel in 728 AH after his ink and writing materials were confiscated.</p>
  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> A self-conscious return to what he understood as the methodology of the Salaf — affirmation of divine attributes in apparent meaning <em>bilā kayf</em>, rejection of allegorical ta'wīl, restrictive view of permissible tawassul, broad polemical engagement with the philosophers (<em>falāsifa</em>) and the Twelver Shīʿa. His methodological signature is the principle that revealed text and sound reason cannot truly conflict, and where they appear to, the appearance is the result of philosophical or rationalist overreach (the central thesis of <em>Darʾ Taʿāruḍ al-ʿAql wa-l-Naql</em>).</p>
  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Majmūʿ al-Fatāwā</em> (a 37-volume fatwa collection), <em>Minhāj al-Sunna al-Nabawiyya</em> (a refutation of Twelver Shīʿism), <em>Darʾ Taʿāruḍ al-ʿAql wa-l-Naql</em>, <em>al-ʿAqīda al-Wāsiṭiyya</em>, <em>Qāʿida Jalīla fī al-Tawassul wa-l-Wasīla</em>.</p>
  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> He is the foundational scholarly authority of the modern Salafī movement, inherited through his student Ibn al-Qayyim al-Jawziyya, then reactivated as a primary reference by Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Wahhāb in the 18th century, and again by 20th-century Salafī scholars (Albānī, Ibn Bāz, Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn, and the Saudi religious establishment).</p>
  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> Imam Taqī al-Dīn al-Subkī (d. 756 AH), a leading Shāfiʿī jurist of his generation, wrote two extended refutations of specific Ibn Taymiyya positions: <em>al-Sayf al-Ṣaqīl fī al-Radd ʿalā Ibn Zafīl</em> and <em>al-Durra al-Muḍiyya fī al-Radd ʿalā Ibn Taymiyya</em>, focused on his ʿaqīdah on direction and his rulings on tawassul/ziyāra. Ibn Ḥajar al-Haytamī (d. 974 AH) extended the same critique in <em>al-Fatāwā al-Ḥadīthiyya</em>. Most strikingly, his own student al-Dhahabī (d. 748 AH), the great Sunnī biographer, wrote a personal letter to him near the end of his life — <em>al-Naṣīḥa al-Dhahabiyya</em> — warning him about the harshness of his polemics and what al-Dhahabī described as the corrosive effect on his readers. Imam Ibn Ḥajar al-ʿAsqalānī (d. 852 AH), the muḥaddith of Egypt, summarised the classical Sunnī assessment in his <em>al-Durar al-Kāmina</em>: a brilliant scholar of ḥadīth and refutation of falsafa, but with specific creedal positions that were neither inherited from earlier authorities nor accepted by mainline Sunnī scholarship.</p>
  <p><strong>Where he aligns and departs.</strong> Ibn Taymiyya was, in the assessment of his own madhhab and of the wider Sunnī establishment of his time, a major scholar with established mastery of ḥadīth and an effective refuter of philosophical and Shīʿī challenges. Where he departed from the four-madhhab consensus was on specific creedal points — affirming a kind of <em>jihah</em> (direction) for Allāh, rejecting the categorical permissibility of tawassul through the deceased, holding kalām to be a blameworthy innovation. The classical Sunnī mainstream did not declare him outside the fold; it did not transmit ʿaqīdah from him.</p>

  <h3>Muḥammad Nāṣir al-Dīn al-Albānī — d. 1420 AH / 1999 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in Shkodër, Albania (1914 CE); his family migrated to Damascus when he was nine. Largely self-taught: he did not pass through the classical Sunnī education path of formal isnād-based ijāzah-bearing teachers in ḥadīth, and instead developed his expertise through extensive personal reading in the Ẓāhiriyya Library in Damascus. He worked initially as a watchmaker before devoting himself full-time to ḥadīth study. He never held a formal teaching post in any of the major Sunnī institutions; he taught informally and through prolific writing.</p>
  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> Independent re-grading of the entire ḥadīth corpus — including reports in <em>Ṣaḥīḥ al-Bukhārī</em> and <em>Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em> — based on his own assessment of isnād authenticity and matn coherence. His operative principle: any ḥadīth, regardless of where it appears, must meet his independent standard. He rejected the four-madhhab framework as a binding methodology, advocating instead for "the strongest evidence" (<em>arjaḥ al-adilla</em>) on each question, derived directly by the qualified individual from the texts.</p>
  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Silsilat al-Aḥādīth al-Ṣaḥīḥa</em>, <em>Silsilat al-Aḥādīth al-Ḍaʿīfa wa-l-Mawḍūʿa</em>, <em>Ṣaḥīḥ wa-Ḍaʿīf al-Jāmiʿ al-Ṣaghīr</em>, <em>Tamām al-Minna fī al-Taʿlīq ʿalā Fiqh al-Sunna</em>, <em>Irwāʾ al-Ghalīl fī Takhrīj Aḥādīth Manār al-Sabīl</em>.</p>
  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> Among the most cited Salafī ḥadīth authorities of the 20th century, particularly in the post-1980 globalisation of Salafī fiqh. His re-classifications have shaped Salafī fatwa practice on questions ranging from prayer to women's dress to permissible recreation.</p>
  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> The Damascene Shāfiʿī scholar Ḥasan ibn ʿAlī al-Saqqāf wrote multiple volumes systematically cataloguing what he identified as al-Albānī's errors: <em>Tanāqudāt al-Albānī al-Wāḍiḥa</em> ("the obvious contradictions of al-Albānī") in three volumes, and his earlier <em>al-Qawl al-Mubīn fī Akhṭāʾ al-Albānī</em>. The Egyptian-Saudi-trained ḥadīth scholar Maḥmūd Saʿīd Mamdūḥ wrote <em>Tanbīh al-Muslim ilā Taʿaddī al-Albānī ʿalā Ṣaḥīḥ Muslim</em>, focused specifically on al-Albānī's downgrading of authentic Muslim aḥādīth. The Moroccan Mālikī muḥaddith Shaykh ʿAbdullāh al-Ghumārī (d. 1993) wrote multiple critical works. The structural critique that recurs across these refutations: al-Albānī had no authoritative ḥadīth ijāzah in the riwāya chain that runs through the canonical Sunnī ḥadīth compilers, and he was nevertheless willing to reverse those compilers' gradings — a methodological move classical Sunnī scholarship considers requires the very ijtihādī qualifications al-Albānī did not possess.</p>
  <p><strong>Where he aligns and departs.</strong> Al-Albānī was a remarkably industrious autodidact whose work brought ḥadīth study into the centre of 20th-century Salafī religious life. His departure from the classical Sunnī mainstream is on a foundational methodological question: whether ijtihād in ḥadīth grading can be exercised by an individual who stands outside the inherited isnād chain of the canonical compilers. The Deobandī, Barelvī, traditional Shāfiʿī, and Mālikī establishments all answer no; al-Albānī answered yes.</p>

  <h3>ʿAbd al-ʿAzīz ibn Bāz — d. 1420 AH / 1999 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in Riyadh (1912 CE) into a religious family. Lost his sight progressively in his youth, becoming totally blind by his early twenties. Educated in the Saudi religious establishment of his era — a small circle of Najdī Wahhābī scholars — and rose through it: judge, then president of the Islamic University of Medina, then head of the Permanent Committee for Iftāʾ, and from 1993 until his death the Grand Mufti of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia.</p>
  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> Strict Salafī Atharī creed — the affirmation of divine attributes in apparent meaning <em>bilā kayf</em>, in line with Ibn Taymiyya. Ḥanbalī fiqh formally, but with willingness to depart from the school when an alternative position appeared to him better-evidenced. Strong views on classical Sunnī devotional practices: rejection of mawlid celebrations as bidʿa, of tawassul through the deceased Prophet ﷺ as a means leading to shirk, of group dhikr in fixed gatherings as bidʿa.</p>
  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Majmūʿ Fatāwā wa-Maqālāt Mutanawwiʿa</em> (his collected fatwas and articles, in many volumes), and a series of teaching commentaries on classical creedal works.</p>
  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> Through the Saudi state's official religious establishment, ibn Bāz's positions shaped both Saudi domestic religious policy and — through Saudi-funded mosques, scholarships, and translations — global Salafī fiqh and ʿaqīdah for the second half of the 20th century.</p>
  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> The most-cited public controversy involved his early fatwa upholding the geocentric model of the universe — affirming that the Earth is stationary and the sun moves around it, citing literal readings of Qurʾānic verses about the sun "running its course." The fatwa was later qualified or revised in some accounts; the original position is still cited in critical scholarship as illustrating a pattern of literalist reading exceeding classical Sunnī interpretive practice. His political fatwas drew sharper criticism: the 1991 fatwa permitting non-Muslim military bases on the Arabian Peninsula during the Gulf War — the same peninsula about which the Prophet ﷺ said "expel the polytheists from the Arabian Peninsula" — was attacked from across the Sunnī spectrum, including from within the Salafī tendency. On classical theological grounds, his positions on tawassul, ziyāra, and the Salafī line on the Ashʿarī/Māturīdī schools are critiqued by scholars across South Asia (the Deobandī and Barelvī establishments), the Levantine traditional Sunnī networks (al-Saqqāf, the Ghumārī family), and West African Mālikī ʿulamāʾ.</p>
  <p><strong>Where he aligns and departs.</strong> Ibn Bāz was a senior, learned, and personally pious figure within the institutional Saudi Salafī establishment. His religious authority operated within that establishment and through the Saudi state. His departures from the classical four-madhhab Sunnī mainstream are precisely the documented Salafī departures — on mawlid, tawassul, ziyāra, group dhikr, and the legitimacy of the Ashʿarī/Māturīdī kalām tradition.</p>

  <h3>Muḥammad ibn Ṣāliḥ al-ʿUthaymīn — d. 1421 AH / 2001 CE</h3>

  <p><strong>Biography.</strong> Born in ʿUnayza, Saudi Arabia (1925 CE). Studied with Saudi Salafī scholars including ʿAbd al-Raḥmān ibn al-Saʿdī (a major teacher of his generation) and ibn Bāz. Held the position of khaṭīb at the Grand Mosque of ʿUnayza for over five decades; member of the Saudi Council of Senior Scholars; taught generations of Saudi-trained Salafī scholars and lay Muslims. Died in Mecca in 2001.</p>
  <p><strong>Methodology.</strong> Atharī ʿaqīdah in the line of Ibn Taymiyya and Ibn al-Qayyim — affirmation of attributes in apparent meaning <em>bilā kayf</em>, rejection of ta'wīl. Ḥanbalī fiqh formally, with the same willingness as ibn Bāz to depart from the madhhab when an alternative position appeared to him better-evidenced. Notably less politically engaged than ibn Bāz; primarily a teacher, expositor, and answerer of practical questions of fiqh and ʿaqīdah for lay Muslims.</p>
  <p><strong>Major works.</strong> <em>Sharḥ al-ʿAqīda al-Wāsiṭiyya</em> (his commentary on Ibn Taymiyya's foundational creedal text), <em>al-Sharḥ al-Mumtiʿ ʿalā Zād al-Mustaqniʿ</em> (a 10-volume Ḥanbalī fiqh commentary, his major scholarly legacy), <em>Sharḥ Riyāḍ al-Ṣāliḥīn</em>, his collected <em>Fatāwā</em>, and many teaching audio-cassette series later published as books.</p>
  <p><strong>Influence.</strong> One of the most widely-respected teachers within the contemporary Salafī tradition. His written commentaries are used as standard textbooks in Salafī higher religious education globally. His audio teaching circulates extensively in English translation among Western Salafī communities.</p>
  <p><strong>Documented criticisms.</strong> His positions on tawassul through the Prophet ﷺ, on the prohibition of mawlid, and on the status of group dhikr follow the Saudi Salafī establishment line and are critiqued from the same classical Sunnī directions documented above. Specific fatwas — including his readings on women's modesty norms, on dealings with non-Salafī Sunnī Muslims (Sufis in particular), and on certain modes of Qurʾān recitation in congregation — have been the subject of pushback from traditional Ḥanbalī scholars who argue that his "willingness to depart from the madhhab" produces results that the Ḥanbalī school's classical scholars did not arrive at. The Damascene Ḥanbalī scholar Saʿīd Ramaḍān al-Būṭī (d. 2013) wrote extensively on what he saw as the methodological problems with Saudi-school Salafī "non-madhhab" fiqh, including the lines of reasoning ibn al-ʿUthaymīn used.</p>
  <p><strong>Where he aligns and departs.</strong> Ibn al-ʿUthaymīn was a learned, productive, and personally respected scholar within his school. His learning is genuine and his fiqh productivity considerable. The points at which he departs from the four-madhhab Sunnī mainstream are again the documented Salafī departures — on mawlid, tawassul, ziyāra, group dhikr, and the broader question of whether the classical kalām-based ʿaqīdah of the Ashʿarī and Māturīdī schools is a faithful transmission of the Salaf's creed.</p>

  <h3>Common ground</h3>

  <p>Each of the four scholars above is recognised by their critics as a serious scholar within their tradition. The classical Sunnī establishment of their respective eras did not declare them outside Islam, did not anathematise them as individuals, and treated their works as worthy of substantive refutation rather than dismissal — a practice the topic pages on this site try to mirror. The disagreements with them are real and specific, anchored in named earlier scholars and named earlier works. Where a critique is advanced on this site, a reader can follow the citation back to its source and assess it themselves.</p>
